        <body>
      
		<pb n="1"/>
			<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Office of the Daily Advertiser</placeName></p>
          <p rend="align(right)"><placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName></p>
          <p rend="align(right)"><date>Decr 30<hi rend="sup">th</hi>. 1850</date></p>
			<p><addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><placeName>Philadelphia</placeName></p>
          <p rend="indent(2)">Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">I have now before me your favors<lb/> dated <date>October 30<hi rend="sup">th</hi></date> &#38; <date>Dec 3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi></date> and note their contents</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">Although the fearful scourge<lb/> which has been doing such dreadful work<lb/> has almost entirely disappeared from <placeName>Kingston</placeName><lb/> still things are inst unsettled&#44; not at<lb/> <placeName>Montego Bay</placeName> and <placeName>Falmouth</placeName> the enemy is<lb/> numbering victims by the hundreds. I am<lb/> therefore unable to do much on your behalf.<lb/> My agent at <placeName>Falmouth</placeName>&#44; <persName>Mr Genge<add>&#63;</add> Lyons</persName>&#44; will<lb/> do his best for you&#44; but at a moment like<lb/> the present I cannot expect any thing to<lb/> be done. The only subscribers I have to<lb/> the <hi rend="underline">Advocate</hi> are <persName>Edwd. Lucas</persName>&#44; &#38; our friend<lb/> <persName>Mr M Collas</persName>. You may rely that so soon as</p>
		<pb n="2"/>
			<p><sic>as</sic> it shall please the almighty to remove<lb/> <add>&#63;</add> our low country&#44; the pestilence I<lb/> shall not be slow in doing my best for<lb/> you. I have advertised yr appeal to the<lb/> Jews of the <placeName>United States</placeName> and the <placeName>W Indies</placeName><lb/> and also the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi>&#44; but no good has<lb/> resulted&#44; probably from the causes I have<lb/> stated. But I must candidly confess&#8212;<lb/> it is no use deceiving you. That I do not<lb/> expect that you will receive much support<lb/> here. I could very easily send you<lb/> a long list of parties willing to become<lb/> &#8220;<hi rend="underline">subscribers</hi>&#8221; to <hi rend="underline">all your works</hi>&#44; but they<lb/> are of that class which more properly<lb/> speaking should be called <hi rend="underline">receivers</hi>&#44; as<lb/> the &#8220;<hi rend="underline">subscription</hi>&#8221; part of the business is the<lb/> last thing they think of. Such parties<lb/> as I may order the paper for I shall<lb/> have no difficulty in procuring pay&#45;<lb/>ment from.</p>
		<pb n="3"/>
          <p rend="indent(1)">There is very little stirring in the way of<lb/> news that will interest you. Poor <persName>Mrs. Peixotto</persName>&#44;<lb/> mother of my friend <persName>Miss Peixotto</persName>&#44; died from<lb/> debility consequent on an attack of Cholera<lb/> a couple of weeks ago&#44; at the age of 62.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">I would advise you that whenever<lb/> you publish your paper that you address<lb/> it &#40;the 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> number&#41; to parties here whose<lb/> names I will send you&#44; with a notice<lb/> that I will receive subscriptions. Please God<lb/> I will send you something Jewish from<lb/> here to come out with which shall make<lb/> the paper interesting and thus catch a few<lb/> subscribers&#44; if possible.</p>
          <p rend="indent(1)">A project is on food here to extend<lb/> the benefits of the &#8220;Hebrew National Institution&#8221;<lb/> by providing for the Board and Lodging of<lb/> a certain number of children and combining<lb/> therewith <del>it</del> an industrial education. The move&#45;<lb/>&#45;ment was set on foot by the <persName>Revd Solomon<lb/> Jacobs</persName> who addressed the Jewish public of the <placeName>Island</placeName><lb/> on the necessity of it&#44; through the <sic>colums</sic> of the<lb/> Daily</p>
		<pb n="4"/>
			<p><hi rend="underline">Daily Advertiser</hi> I send you a copy of the<lb/> appeal made to the public by the Committee<lb/> who have taken the matter in hand. To<lb/> save postage I have enclosed the same<lb/> in a small package of my papers to your<lb/> address. Perhaps you may notice the<lb/> matter in the <hi rend="underline">Occident</hi>. I may here after<lb/> give you some account of a reform I<lb/> am trying to introduce at our adjunto<lb/> &#40;the English &#38; German <sic>shool</sic>&#41; I mean a<lb/> reform in the <hi rend="underline">Constitution of the Vestry</hi><lb/> <hi rend="underline">not in the mode of worship</hi></p>
          <p rend="indent(1)"><persName>Mr <add>&#63;</add></persName> has this moment left<lb/> me. He desires me to convey his regards<lb/> so does <persName>Mr Peixotto</persName>&#44; <persName>Miss P</persName> and all<lb/> the family</p>
          <p rend="indent(3)">I am Dear Sir</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)">Respectfully yours</p>
          <p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Isaac <add>&#63;</add></persName></p>
			<p><persName>Miss Peixotto</persName> begs that you<lb/> will be good enough to com&#45;<lb/>&#45;municate to her friends the demise of<lb/> her mother and to say that in consequence<lb/> of her affliction she is unable now to write</p>
          
          <div>
